&lt;tt&gt;
&gt; Does HERITRIX handle cookies? - in the UI there are two text-fiels for &lt;BR&gt;
&gt; save and load cookie-file !&lt;BR&gt;
&lt;BR&gt;
Yes it does. Handling of cookies is done by default.&lt;BR&gt;
&lt;BR&gt;
The load cookies option allows an operator to pre-load existing cookies file (in the Netscape&#39;s &lt;BR&gt;
format.) Specified load cookie-file is pre-loaded before the first document fetch.&lt;BR&gt;
FYI: If your are an IE user you can use File- Import Export wizard to export IE cookies to the &lt;BR&gt;
Netscape format.&lt;BR&gt;
&lt;BR&gt;
The save cookies option allows an operator to specify a file where the cookies will be saved to &lt;BR&gt;
after the crawl is done. Only non-expired cookies stored during the crawl will be saved to this file.&lt;BR&gt;
&lt;BR&gt;
&gt; When the crawler runs - does it save cookies recieved and deliver them &lt;BR&gt;
&gt; again?&lt;BR&gt;
&lt;BR&gt;
Yes, the crawler is keeping a state of all cookies.&lt;BR&gt;
&lt;BR&gt;
&gt; I crawled a specific site: &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.hkhkronprinsen.dk&quot;&gt;http://www.hkhkronprinsen.dk&lt;/a&gt; - The crawl went &lt;BR&gt;
&gt; fine - but when I look at the material all HTML-files has PHP-errors in &lt;BR&gt;
&gt; the top (session-ID-error originating from either missing or alternated &lt;BR&gt;
&gt; cookie)&lt;BR&gt;
&lt;BR&gt;
Could you please provide more info. Maybe an excerpt of one of these pages. HTTP headers would be great.&lt;BR&gt;
&lt;BR&gt;
&lt;BR&gt;
&gt; Does cookies undergo some character-encoding?&lt;BR&gt;
&lt;BR&gt;
No. Cookies handling is done via HTTP headers and to my knowledge http headers are not encoded.&lt;BR&gt;
